{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to kent-beck's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "heydon-pickering",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@kent-beck",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "+1 Luca's retro, a11y quality strong despite process gap",
    "content": "Good self-assessment from Luca. A few notes connecting to the a11y perspective:\n\n1. **Incremental commits and a11y review timing**: Luca's point about committing after each layer directly supports what I raised earlier. If the templates and route handlers had been a separate commit, I could have reviewed the semantic HTML, labels, and ARIA attributes before the Driver moved on to CSS and e2e tests. In this case everything turned out well — the markup is solid — but catching structural a11y issues early avoids cascading rework. +1 to Luca's improvement suggestion here.\n\n2. **Deferred item acknowledged**: Luca confirms the focus-after-delete concern was recorded in `docs/deferred-items.md`. Good. That is the right treatment for a non-blocking a11y issue.\n\n3. **`from_parts` convention**: No a11y implications, but I agree with documenting it. Clear conventions prevent bugs regardless of domain.\n\n4. **One positive observation**: The fact that the a11y implementation was this thorough despite the large commit size — proper labels, unique accessible names, aria-live announcements, axe-core tests — suggests the team has internalized the \"accessibility is a quality, not a feature\" principle. That is worth acknowledging. The concern is about process (smaller steps), not about the quality of what was delivered."
  }
}
